I based this cat clown girl off my fatass floof...
body:
I don’t think i ever posted this and if i did then sorry for the repeat lol

I based this cat clown girl off my fatass floof gremlin. She has a giant eye on her belly to represent how my cat will always have a creepy stare if her eyes are opened more than a squint and will bore her gaze into your soul. My cat likes staring at people ._.

Also ignore the word sweet I was trying to doodle my clown ocs, including this new one, in a thing for that “Smile! Sweet! Sister! Sadistic! Surprise! Service!” Thing and she’s the first one done. I’m gonna digitalize it before I post the whole thing lol.

She still needs a name so feel free to suggest, otherwise i might just name her after my cat too X3

summary: 印 in: Seals In the last article, you see the red seal next to the idiogram 亥. Recently はんこ ‘hanko’ seals are very popular among...
caption:
印 in: Seals

In the last article, you see the red seal next to the idiogram 亥.

Recently はんこ ‘hanko’ seals are very popular among foreigners who visit Japan, but ‘hanko’ is different from ‘in’.
‘In’ is used in totally artistic way.
Its design and position is also a part of the art work.

Historically we use ‘in’ seals with our autograph.  
Originally it was formal to use 2 seals after artist name, but many SHOKA, Japanese calligraphers who make modern, contemporary works often use only 1 seal.
We don’t have only one ‘in’ seal for one artist.
We choose a suitable ‘in’ seal for each work.
In an exhibition, it is also fun to see the variation of ‘in’ seals.
For me, coordinating ‘in’ and my work is a big fun.
Most of my ‘in’ seals are made by myself.
Especially when I start a new way of expression, I make a new ‘in’ for the new works.
